definition.value: A (3R)-3-hydroxyacyl group derived from (3R)-3-hydroxydecanoic acid.
A trans-2-enoyl group derived from trans-dec-2-enoic acid.
An antagonist that binds to and activates aryl hydrocarbon receptors (AhRs).
Any univalent carboacyl group that is derived from a trans-2-enoic acid.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol)(1-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate group of 1-oleoyl-2-lauroyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol); major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol)(1-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate group of 1-palmitoyl-2-lauroyl-sn-glycero-3-phospho-(1'-sn-glycerol); major species at pH 7.3.
Any member of the class of isoflavans in which one or more ring hydrogens are replaced by methoxy groups.
A (3R)-3-hydroxyacyl group derived from (3R)-3-hydroxypalmitoic acid.
A trans-2-enoyl group derived from trans-hexadec-2-enoic acid.
A glycine derivative that is glycinamide in which one of the amino hydrogens is replaced by a 9-beta-D-ribofuranosylpurin-6-yl group.
A benzoate ester resulting from the formal condensation of benzoic acid with the phenolic hydroxy group of 17beta-estradiol.
A glutathione conjugate obtained by formation of a thioselenide link between the thiol group of glutathione and the selenol group of 1-seleno-N-acetyl-D-galactosamine.
A macrolide antibiotic that is 20-oxotylactone having a 5-O-beta-D-mycaminosyl residue attached at position 6.
A monosaccharide derivative that is  N-acetyl-beta-D-galactosamine in which the anomeric hydroxy group is replaced by a methylseleno group.
A macrolide antibiotic that is tylonolide having a beta-D-mycaminosyl residue attached at position 5.
An organoselenium compound that is seleninic acid in which the hydrogen attached to selenium is replaced by a methyl group.
An extended flavonoid resulting from the formal fusion of a benzene ring with the f side of flavone.
A stable isotope of boron with relative atomic mass 10.0129370, 19.9 atom percent natural abundance and nuclear spin 3+.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-22-hydroxydocosahexaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A polyunsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the two diphosphate OH groups of alpha-NAD(1+); major species at pH 7.3.
An organophosphate oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of alpha-NADP(+); major species at pH 7.3.

label.value: EC 1.10.99.* (oxidoreductases acting on diphenols and related substances as donors, other acceptors) inhibitor

definition.value: An EC 1.10.* (oxidoreductase acting on diphenols and related substances as donors) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any such enzyme in the EC 1.10.99.* category.

An EC 1.10.99.* (oxidoreductases acting on diphenols and related substances as donors, other acceptors) inhibitor that interferes with the action of ribosyldihydronicotinamide dehydrogenase (quinone), EC 1.10.99.2.
A disaccharide consisting beta-D-glucosyl and D-gluconic acid residues joined by a (1->4)-linkage.

label.value: EC 2.3.3.* (acyltransferase converting acyl to alkyl group on transfer) inhibitor

definition.value: An EC 2.3.* (acyltransferase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of an acyltransferase which converts the acyl group to an alkyl group on transfer (EC 2.3.3.*).
An EC 2.3.3.* (acyltransferase converting acyl to alkyl group on transfer) inhibitor that interferes with the action of citrate (Si)-synthase, EC 2.3.3.1.
An EC 3.1.3.* (phosphoric monoester hydrolase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of 4-nitrophenylphosphatase (EC 3.1.3.41).
A disaccharide consisting beta-D-glucosyl and D-glucuronic acid residues joined by a (1->3)-linkage.

An iridoid monoterpenoid that is 1,4a,5,6,7,7a-hexahydrocyclopenta[c]pyran-4-carboxylic acid substituted at positions 1 and 7 by hydroxy and methyl groups respectively; the aglycone of 7-deoxyloganic acid.
A selenoamino acid that is L-selenomethionine in which the methyl group attached to the selenium is replaced by a 5'-adenosyl group.
A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-alanine in which one of the methyl hydrogens is replaced by a 5-oxoisoxazolin-2-yl group.
A member of the class of isoxazoles that is L-alanine in which one of the methyl hydrogens is replaced by a 5-oxoisoxazolin-4-yl group.
A  non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-phenylalanine in which one of the benzyl hydrogens is replaced by a methyl group (the 3S-stereoisomer).

A substituted aniline that is 2,4-dibromoaniline which is substituted at position 6 by a [cyclohexyl(methyl)amino]methyl group. It is used (as the monohydrochloride salt) as a mucolytic for the treatment of respiratory disorders associated with productive cough (i.e. a cough characterised by the production of sputum).
A omega-hydroxy-long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 14-hydroxymyristic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A compound that alters the structure of mucus so as to decrease its viscosity and thereby facilitate its removal by ciliary action and expectoration. Compare with antitussives, which suppress the cough reflex, and expectorants, which are considered to increase the volume of secretions in the respiratory tract, so facilitating their removal by ciliary action and coughing.

Compounds that are considered to increase the volume of secretions in the respiratory tract, so facilitating their removal by ciliary action and coughing. Compare with mucolytics, which decrease the viscosity of mucus, facilitating its removal by ciliary action and expectoration, and antitussives, which suppress the cough reflex.
A cyclic peptide antibiotic that is A47934 lacking the O-sulfo group; it is produced by a strain of Streptomyces toyocaensis.
An alpha-aminoacyl group derived from N,N-dimethyl-L-alanine.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion that is the pentaanion of (S)-3-hydroxytetradecanedioyl-CoA, arising from deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and carboxylic acid functions; major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion that is the pentaanion of trans-2-tetradecenedioyl-CoA, arising from deprotonation of phosphate, diphosphate and carboxylic acid functions; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of bromhexine. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
An acyl-CoA oxoanion that is the pentaanion of 3-oxotetradecanedioyl-CoA, arising from deprotonation of the phosphate, diphosphate and carboxylic acid functions; major species at pH 7.3.
A methyl-L-alanine in which both the amino hydrogens of L-alanine are replaced by methyl groups.
An N-acylurea that is urea in which one of the hydrogens is replaced by a 2-bromo-3-methybutanoyl group.
A 2-bromo-N-carbamoyl-3-methylbutanamide that has R configuration.
A 2-bromo-N-carbamoyl-3-methylbutanamide that has S configuration.
A carbotricyclic compound that is tetradecahydrophenanthrenewhich is substituted by an ethyl group at position 7 and by methyl groups at positions 1, 1, 4a, and 7 (the 4aR,4bS,7S,8aS,10aS isomer).
